They argue that one must look at all provisions not in isolation, but in a universe where they are not mutually independent. They consider those monitored by the IRRC for institutional investors and researchers, which amount to 24. Prior research has id\'92d a relationship between the IRRC provisions in the aggregate and firm value. one particular study showed that a broad index based on all 24 provisions that are given equal weight was negatively correlated with firm value as measured by Tobin\'92s Q as well as stockholder returns during the 90\'92s. Used widely. Authors argue that there is no a-priori reason that all 24 should be relevant. this study aims to find out which are important and which aren\'92t.   \
\
Begin with hypothesis for testing, including rational behind the 6 provisions they pick. They include in this list of proviso all those that have systematically drawn substantial opposition from institutional investors voting on precatory resolutions (non-binding, https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Shareholder_resolution). \
	> Is this a good idea? Assuming that the provisions most accounted with firm value are those that investors argue against\'85makes sense in that they can be assumed to be acting in their own self interest and thus have id\'92d already those provisions that would be harmful. \
They also conduct their own analysis of their consequences and conduct interviews with M&A practitioners.\
\
Of the 6, 4 set constitutional limits of shareholder voting power, which is the primary power shareholders have. That is, they limit the extent to which shareholders can impose their will on management. The other two are the most well-known measures taken in prep for a hostile offer (pp and gp). The authors assign a score from 0-6 to each company based on the given provision they have in the given year or month. They find that their index is monotonically (in this case, always decreases) and economically significantly negatively correlated with Tobin\'92s Q. Also, the provisions in the E index appear to be largely driving the correlation that the IRRC provisions in the aggregate have with Tobin\'92s Q. They find no evidence that the eighteen provisions not in the E index are negatively correlated with Tobin\'92s Q. \
